## Migration to .NET 8

Your code uses **three deprecated APIs**: `Thread.Abort()`, `ThreadAbortException` catch, and `Thread.ResetAbort()`. All throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work (replaces ThreadAbortException catch)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we decide whether to continue via the loop condition.
                // Loop will exit naturally since token is cancelled.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Not needed — loop condition handles continuation |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` before abort | `Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` |
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` (thread-safe by design) |

### Critical Pitfalls

1. **`GetNextItem()` must accept the token** — If it blocks (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take`), replace with `Take(token)` or `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()`. Without this, cancellation stalls until the blocking call returns on its own.

2. **Cancellation is not immediate** — Unlike `Thread.Abort` which injected an exception anywhere, cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or token-aware APIs). Add checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running.

3. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — It's `IDisposable` and leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed.

4. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` deeper in the call chain** — Only catch it at this top-level loop. Let it propagate from inner methods.

5. **`Thread.Join` can hang** — If your code has a blocking call that doesn't honor the token, `Join` will block indefinitely. Consider `Join(timeout)` and logging a warning if the thread doesn't exit.

### If `GetNextItem` blocks on a `BlockingCollection<T>`

```csharp
// Before (blocks forever, only Thread.Abort could interrupt):
var item = _queue.Take();

// After (wakes up immediately on cancellation):
var item = _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
```

### If code is truly uncooperative (can't pass token)

Move it to a child **process** and call `Process.Kill()` — this is the only safe forced-termination mechanism in modern .NET.
